<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>NON-PERSONAL INFORMATION SHARING AGREEMENT</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Marine Conservation Society</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e Marine Conservation Society (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS) is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> charity dedicated to the protection of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’s seas, shores and wildlife. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> campaigns for clean seas and beaches, sustainable fisheries, protection of marine life and their habitats, and the sensitive use of our marine resources for future generations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> produces the annual Good Beach Guide, the Good Fish Guide on sustainable seafood, organises volunteer projects and surveys such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Big Weekend and Basking Shark Watch and works closely with the UK Government and devolved administrations on the development and implementation of marine laws and policies.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS is a core member of the Break the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ag </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">abit coalition that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> includes The Campaign to Protect Rural England, Keep Britain Tidy, Surfers Against Sewage, Thames 21 and Greener upon Thames. The coalition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has been campaigning for a charge on all single use carrier bags.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS has campaigned for and strongly supports the introduction of a charge on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">single use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">plastic bags on the grounds that plastic bags are an ubiquitous, widely dispersed, long-lasting, unsightly and hazardous form of litter that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> whether whole or broken down into micro-particles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> pose a threat to marine wildlife </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">many of which are already endangered or threatened by human exploitation or activities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS would urge the committee and the Government to follow the Welsh scheme which covers all single use bags and retailers. This would ensure  an integrated, tried and tested system in place across mainland UK which has been effective and popular with retailers and consumers alike, and not to fragment the scheme so that there are potentially two systems in play.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> believe that any charge should cover all single use bags. This  is  to ensure that other forms of single use packaging do not simply replace plastic shopping bags - replacing free plastic shopping bags with free paper or biodegradable bags is not a solution. The public should be encouraged to reuse bags, rather than replacing one form of disposable bag for another.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We also believe that all retailers should be covered by the scheme. The exclusion of SMEs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (or organisations with less than 250 employees as stated in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘Call for Evidence’)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is a matter of considerable concern. Many of the businesses contributing to beach and coastal litt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">er, in particular, will fall in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to this category. This exemption could prevent a reduction in coastal litter from SME sources.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is also necessary to include SMEs to implement Government’s stated intent to be as “c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">onsistent as practical with the charging scheme in the other countries of the UK, in order to maintain a coherent regulatory environment” and “to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">minimise confusion for the public and additional burden on cross-border organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">”.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">(1)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> It would seem to be perverse to bring in this exemption which the majority of SMEs themselves do not welcome.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The ‘Call for Evidence’ states in paragraph 6 that “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Experience from the Welsh and Northern Irish carrier bag charges suggests that this will significantly reduce the number of plastic bags distributed in this country. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> saw a 76% decrease in single-use carrier bag distribution in the year following the charge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with the exemptions of certain types of bags and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with fewer than 250 employees, MCS believe that the reduction in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> will not be as successful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Although Bags for Life are also excluded from the charge, provision should be made so that they can be included at a later date. This is to counter any possible perverse effect of a large increase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the purchasing of Bags for Life.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">To avoid the charge becoming a profit making exercise for businesses, there should be strong direction from the Government that any mon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">es raised should go to good causes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Legislation already exists that provides the powers to i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ntrodu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ce a charge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the Climate Change Act 2008. Section 77 and Schedul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e 6 of the Act enables the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government to require sellers of goods to charge for single-use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(plastic) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">bags that they supply to their customers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As this power relates to a charge rather than a ban, and given the current political climate, we feel a charge is more appropriate at this time. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Impacts of plastic bags </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> wide beach clean and survey organised by MCS that has taken place every September since 1993. During the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 2012 event 4,092 plastic bags were found on 238 beaches around the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> over one weekend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(2)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This equates to an average of 45 bags for every kilometre of coastline surveyed. Plastic bags ranked number 13 in the top 20 most common litter items recorded, accounting for 2.2% of all beach litter. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Compared to levels in 1996, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> average density of plastic bags found during </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has increased by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">over 20%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">35.7 bags/km to 45.1 bags/km.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">During the 2012 International Coastal Clean-up (ICC), which took place in over 97 countries worldwide, 1,019,902 plastic bags were found, accounting for 9% of all litter found</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A study on the degradation of various types of plastic bags (standard, degradable and biodegradable) in the gastrointestinal fluids of Green and Loggerhead turtles showed that after 49 days the standard and degradable bags showed negligible signs of degradation. Although the biodegradable bags showed mass losses of between 3-9% over the same period, the authors concluded that this was so slow that morbidity could still occur.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(3)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A further study looked at the degradation times of various types of plastics bags – compostable, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">oxo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> -degradable and standard plastic in seawater and found that decreases in temperature and UV light along with bio-fouling of material led to increased degradation times. After 40 weeks the samples received 90% less UV light and although the compostable plastics had completely degraded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the other materials lost only approximately 2% of their surface area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> With regard to ‘biodegradable’ plastics, they concluded that “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the efficiency of such materials as a means of reducing harm caused by marine litter is questionable if long exposures are required for degradation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Changes in bag us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">age following other UK schemes</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A carrier bag charging scheme was introduced in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in October 2011.The Welsh scheme has proved immensely popular, with over 70% of consumers supporting it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In July 2012, John Griffiths, the then Minister for Environment and Sustainable Development in the Welsh Government, said in a written statement that retailers had estimated a fall in single-use bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">issued of between 70-96%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a levy was introduced in April 2013. Provisional figures released by DoE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">NI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for the first quarter of 2013-14 suggest that some supermarkets could see</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a reduction of over 80%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in the number of bags given out.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> there has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">decrease in the number of bags given out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">betwe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">en </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 70% to 90%. Figures show that approximately 90</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">% of shoppers now use reusable/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">long life bags, 6% use cardboard boxes, 4% pla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">stic bags and 1% other means.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A poll commissioned by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Break The Bag Habit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Coalition found that if people were asked to pay just 5p for new carrier bags, three quarte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rs of those surveyed (75%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">) would try to cut down the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> number of new bags they used.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There may be an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">initial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increase in the sales of Bags for Life. This happened in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and was expected within the first year of the charge coming into place; Welsh officials have confirmed they will update legislation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">if an unwelcome trend continues. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Scottish Government have determined that following the introduction of a charge Bags for Life usage will increase by 30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> but the use of thin gauge carrier bags will fall by 440</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">illion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">When </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> introduced the charge on plastic bags there were reports of a 77% increase in the sale of plastic kitchen bags, which equates to 70 million bags. However, the 90% reduction in carrier bags equated to a reduction of one billion bags, leaving a net reduction of 930 million bags. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Additionally bin liner type bags are rarely found as litter or ingested by wildlife.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Impacts on budgets/jobs</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Impacts on household budgets are likely to be minimal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5p charge and an annua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">l per capita usage of 130 bags would equate to £6.50 per year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">if people kept up their same level of usage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. From the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> experiences this is unlikely to happen as the majority of people start to reuse bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As it is not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (compulsory), but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a charge (voluntary), people can elect for it not to affect their household budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Public support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increased to 70% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> during the recession. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The majority of conventional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">plastic carrier bags in the UK are imported from the Far East and China</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">These imports all involve transportation, with related pollution costs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the number of people working purely on plastic b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ags in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is extremely low. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Jobs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> also be created as a result of a charge, both in environmental projects funded by the charge’s proceeds, and in the industry for robust reusable bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Creative ways of helping protect indigenous industry could be developed, for example, by stipulating a minimum recycled content of plastic bags, which would make it more difficult for overseas manufacturers to compete.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Exemption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">s for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">England</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS is very concerned by the exemptions proposed for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and believes this will create confusion for retailers and consumers alike. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ll single use bags, regardless of material, should be charged for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  There is nothing to be gained from replacing one free bag with another.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This makes no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">environmental or economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sense and will not achieve the change in behaviour which is key to reducing our waste over all.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that if all retailers have to comply with the regulations this will create a level playing field which will make the regulations much easier to implement and enforce. It would be much better to follow the Welsh example which has a basic charge on all single use bags regardless of material types. This scheme is efficient and popular with retailers and consumers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is also likely to follow this system. Why complicate a system so that there are potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> different sche</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mes in operation in Mainland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">? This is also contrary to the Government’s stated intention of introducing a streamlined system.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Association of Convenience Stores</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (ACS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> themselves have stated they want their members to be included within the scheme as they think that charging is the most effective measure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">reduce bag usage. Fundamentally they think being exempt from the scheme will create more of a burden than if they’re part of it.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">pers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> comm.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">o </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Break the Bag Habit group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ACS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> actively want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the English scheme to mirror Wales and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to be exempt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">from having to report on income. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">heir research shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&gt;90</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">% of retailers in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> give the money away without requiring reporting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Exemptions of certain bag types</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Exemptions for paper and biodegradable bags will have the perverse effect of increasing the number of these bags in circulation, both of which have environmental implications. It would also seem to go against the government’s commitment to ‘working to reduce litter’ and to achieving a zero waste economy as detailed in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Waste Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For both paper and ‘biodegradable’ bags it is important to note that this is simply replacing one form of free</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, single use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> bag with another</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:line-through"> </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Biodegradable’ bags</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">MCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">serious concerns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">regarding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the impact that any ‘biodegradable’ bag could have on the plastic recycling sector. Recycling is a key component of reducing environmental impact and money should be spent to improve overall recycling and innovation within this industry, not on producing another single use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> throw away item</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Additionally giving the label ‘biodegradable’ to a bag would seem to imply that it is acceptable to dispose of this item into the environment, thereby increasing littering.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">At present the only truly biodegradable bags are those which are produced from plant material and are compostable. However:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Crops to produce the bags may be grown on land that could be better used for food.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Most are only compostable in industrial compostable situations and only compost very slowly (if at all) in a home composter.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If mixed in with recyclable plastics </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">can increase the cost of recycling or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">contaminate it, totally preventing recycling.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:16.5pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 45.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has an obligation to reduce biodegradable materials going to our landfills. Compostable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> or biodegradable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> bags would increase this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">making it harder for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to meet its legal waste obligations and increase the amounts of methane gases generated. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Paper bags </span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It has been estimated that paper bags have a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">carbon footprint roughly f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">our times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that of conventional plastic bags </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. They affect the environment in the following ways:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">(9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">)</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Water consumption</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Eutrophication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of rivers, lakes, etc due to pollutants released to water</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">during the manufacture of the paper</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Transport – more greenhouse gas emissions </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:7.9pt 0pt 7.9pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Production of solid waste</span></li></ul></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Defra (2013). Paragraphs 10 and 60. Single-Use Plastic Bag Charge for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Call for Evidence. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Marine Conservation Society (2013). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Beachwatch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Big Weekend 2012: methods and results.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Müller</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, C., Townsend, K. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Matschullat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, J. (2012) Experimental degradation of polymer shopping bags (standard and degradable plastic and biodegradable) in the gastrointestinal fluids of sea turtles. Science of the Total Environment. Volume 416: 464-467</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">O’Brine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, T., Thompson, R.C.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(2010) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Degradation of plas